[49m[38;5;9m- 888     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Error handling and retries.** Every external call (HealthLake queries, SageMaker endpoint invocation, DynamoDB writes, SNS publishes) needs try/except blocks with exponential backoff. The adaptive retry config helps, but you also need circuit breakers for when a downstream service is fully down. A failed score should never silently disappear; it should land in a dead-letter queue for retry.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      888[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Error handling and retries.** Every external call (HealthLake queries, SageMaker endpoint invocation, DynamoDB writes, SNS publishes) needs try/except blocks with exponential backoff. The adaptive retry config helps, but you also need circuit breakers for when a downstream service is fully down. A failed score should never silently disappear; it should land in an SQS dead letter queue for retry. Set a CloudWatch alarm on DLQ depth > 0, run a daily retry Lambda to reprocess failures, and escalate to manual review for any patient unscored after 24 hours.
[0m[49m[39m  889, 889[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 890     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Feature assembly from real data sources.** This example generates synthetic features. In production, you'd query HealthLake for the current encounter (diagnoses, procedures, medications, labs), query your claims warehouse or feature store for historical utilization (prior admissions, ED visits), and compute derived features (Elixhauser score, medication complexity) in real time. That feature assembly step is typically the most complex and fragile part of the pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      890[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Feature assembly from real data sources.** This example generates synthetic features. In production, you'd query HealthLake for the current encounter (diagnoses, procedures, medications, labs) and pull pre-computed historical features from a DynamoDB feature store (keyed by patient_id, populated nightly by Glue). This hybrid approach keeps scoring latency under 500ms even for patients with complex multi-year histories. For patients not yet in the feature store (new to your system), fall back to real-time HealthLake queries for historical data.
